# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: archaeplastida
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:archaeplastida/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:archaeplastida/accessory-pigment] The result is that, in vivo, a composite absorption spectrum of all these pigments is broadened and flattened such that a wider range of visible and infrared radiation is absorbed by plants and algae.
[src:archaeplastida/accessory-pigment] Most photosynthetic organisms do not absorb green light well, thus most remaining light under leaf canopies in forests or under water with abundant plankton is green, a spectral effect called the "green window".
[src:archaeplastida/accessory-pigment] Organisms such as some cyanobacteria and red algae contain accessory phycobiliproteins that absorb green light reaching these habitats.
[src:archaeplastida/accessory-pigment] In aquatic ecosystems, it is likely that the absorption spectrum of water, along with gilvin and tripton (dissolved and particulate organic matter, respectively), determines phototrophic niche differentiation.
[src:archaeplastida/accessory-pigment] The six shoulders in the light absorption of water between wavelengths 400 and 1100 nm correspond to troughs in the collective absorption of at least twenty diverse species of phototrophic bacteria.
[src:archaeplastida/accessory-pigment] Another effect is due to the overall trend for water to absorb low frequencies, while gilvin and tripton absorb higher ones.
[src:archaeplastida/accessory-pigment] This is why open ocean appears blue and supports yellow species such as *Prochlorococcus*, which contains divinyl-chlorophyll *a* and *b*.
[src:archaeplastida/accessory-pigment] *Synechococcus*, colored red with phycoerythrin, is adapted to coastal bodies, while phycocyanin allows Cyanobacteria to thrive in darker inland waters.
[src:archaeplastida/acinetactis] The validity and classification of this genus is contested.
[src:archaeplastida/acinetactis] In 1914, Adolf Pascher cast doubt on *Acinetactis*, suggesting that it was a junior synonym of *Dimorpha mutans*.
[src:archaeplastida/acinetactis] Cavalier-Smith classified *Acinetactis* as a heliomonad in 1993.
[src:archaeplastida/acinetactis] Bass et al. suggested in 2009 that the genus was a cercozoan in the class Granofilosea.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:archaeplastida/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The **actinophryids** are an order of heliozoa, a polyphyletic array of amoebae.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] They are common in fresh water and occasionally found in marine and soil habitats.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Actinophryids are unicellular and roughly spherical in shape, with many axopodia that radiate outward from the cell body.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Axopodia are a type of pseudopodia that are supported by hundreds of microtubules arranged in interlocking spirals and forming a needle-like internal structure or axoneme.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Small granules, extrusomes, that lie under the membrane of the body and axopodia capture flagellates, ciliates and small metazoa that make contact with the arms.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Actinophryids are largely aquatic protozoa with a spherical cell body and many needle-like axopodia.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] They resemble the shape of a sun due to this structure, which is the inspiration for their common name: heliozoa, or "sun-animalcules".
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Their bodies, without arms, range in size from a few tens of micrometers to slightly under a millimeter across.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The outer region of cell body is often vacuolated.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The endoplasm of actinophryids is less vacuolated than the outer layer, and a sharp boundary layer may be seen by light microscopy.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The organisms can be either mononucleate, with a single, well defined nucleus in the center of the cell body, or multinucleate, with 10 or more nuclei located under the outer vacuolated layer of cytoplasm.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The cytoplasm of actinophryids is often granular, similar to that of *Amoeba*.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Actinophryid cells may fuse when feeding, creating larger aggregated organisms.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Fine granules that occur just under the cell membrane are used up when food vacuoles form to enclose prey.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Actinophryids may also form cysts when food is not readily available.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] A layer of siliceous plates is deposited under the cell membrane during the encystment process.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are common in these organisms, which are presumed to use them to maintain body volume by expelling fluids to compensate for the entry of water by osmosis.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Contractile vacuoles are visible as clear bulges from the surface of the cell body that slowly fill then rapidly deflate, expelling their contents into the environment.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The most distinctive characteristic of the actinophryids is their axopodia.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] These axopodia consist of a central, rigid rod which is coated in a thin layer of ectoplasm.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] In *Actinophrys* the axonemes end on the surface of the central nucleus, and in the multicellular *Actinosphaerium* they end at or near nuclei.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The axonemes are composed of microtubules arranged in a double spiral pattern characteristic of the order.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Due to their long, parallel construction, these microtubules demonstrate strong birefringence.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] These axopodia are used for prey capture, in movement, cell fusion and perhaps division.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] They are stiff but may flex especially near their tips, and are highly dynamic, undergoing frequent construction and destruction.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] When used to collect prey items, two methods of capture have been noted, termed axopodial flow and rapid axopodial contraction.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Axopodial flow involves the slow movement of a prey item along the surface of the axopod as the ectoplasm itself moves, while rapid axopodial contraction involves the collapse of the axoneme's microtubule structure.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] This behavior has been documented in many species, including *Actinosphaerium nucleofilum*, *Actinophrys sol*, and *Raphidiophrys contractilis*.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The rapid axopodial contraction occurs at high speed, often in excess of 5mm/s or tens of body lengths per second.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The axopodial contractions have been shown to be highly sensitive to environmental factors such as temperature and pressure as well as chemical signals like Ca2+ and colchicine.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Reproduction in actinophryids generally takes place via fission, where one parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] For multinucleate heliozoa, this process is plasmotomic as the nuclei are not duplicated prior to division.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] It has been observed that reproduction appears to be a response to food scarcity, with an increased number of divisions following the removal of food and larger organisms during times of food excess.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Actinophryids also undergo autogamy during times of food scarcity.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] This is better described as genetic reorganization than reproduction, as the number of individuals produced is the same as the initial number.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Nonetheless, it serves as a way to increase genetic diversity within an individual which may improve the likelihood of expressing favorable genetic traits.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Plastogamy has also been extensively documented in actinophryids, especially in multinucleate ones.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* were observed to combine freely without the combination of nuclei, and this process sometimes resulted in more or less individuals than originally combined.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] This process is not caused merely by contact between two individuals but can be caused by damage to the cell body.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Under unfavourable conditions, some species will form a cyst.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] This is often the product of autogamy, in which case the cysts produced are zygotes.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Cells undergoing this process withdraw their axopodia, adhere to the substrate, and take on an opaque and grayish appearance.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] This cyst then divides until only uninucleate cells remain.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] The cyst wall is thickly layered 7–8 times and includes gelatinous layers, layers of silica plates, and iron.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Originally placed in Heliozoa (Sarcodina), the actinophryids are now understood to be part of the stramenopiles.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] They are unrelated to centrohelid and desmothoracid heliozoa with which they had been previously classified.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] There are several genera included within this classification.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] *Actinophrys* are smaller and have a single, central nucleus.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] Most have a cell body 40–50 micrometer in diameter with axopods around 100 μm in length, though this varies significantly.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] *Actinosphaerium* are several times larger, from 200 to 1000 μm in diameter, with many nuclei and are found exclusively in fresh water.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] A third genus, *Camptonema*, has a debated status.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] It has been observed once and was treated as a junior subjective synonym of *Actinosphaerium* by Mikrjukov & Patterson in 2001, but as a valid genus by Cavalier-Smith & Scoble (2013).
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] *Heliorapha* is a further debated taxon, it being a new generic vehicle for the species *azurina* that was initially assigned to the genus *Ciliophrys*.
[src:archaeplastida/actinophryid] According to the latest review of actinophryid classifications, they are organized into two genera and six species.
[src:archaeplastida/aestivation-botany] Aestivation can be an important taxonomic diagnostic; for example Malvaceae flower buds have valvate sepals, with the exception of the genera *Fremontodendron* and *Chiranthodendron*, which have sometimes been misplaced as a result.
[src:archaeplastida/aestivation-botany] The terms used to describe aestivation are the same as those used to describe leaf vernation.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] The stems of *Aglaophyton* were round in cross-section, smooth, unornamented, and up to about 6mm in diameter.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] Kidston and Lang interpreted the plant as growing upright, to about 50 cm in height, but Edwards has re-interpreted it as having prostrate habit, with shorter aerial axes of about 15 cm height.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] The axes branched dichotomously, the aerial axes branching at a comparatively wide angle of up to 90°, and were terminated with elliptical, thick-walled sporangia, which when mature, opened by spiral slits, so that the sporangia appear to be spiral in form.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] Sporangia contained many identical spores (isospores) bearing trilete marks.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] The spores may therefore be interpreted as meiospores, the product of meiotic divisions, and thus the plants described by Edwards and by Kidston and Lang were diploid, sporophytes.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] Edwards reinterpreted the species as non-vascular plant and renamed it *Aglaophyton major*.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] The male gametophyte of the species has been formally described, which was assigned to a new form taxon *Lyonophyton rhyniensis*, but is now properly referred to as an *Aglaophyton* gametophyte.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] The Rhynie chert bears many examples of male and female gametophytes, which are loosely similar in their construction to the sporophyte phase, down to bearing rhizoids.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] In 2004, Crane et al. published a cladogram for the polysporangiophytes which places *Aglaophyton* as a sister of the vascular plants (tracheophytes), with the Horneophytopsida being sister to both.
[src:archaeplastida/aglaophyton] The basis of the cladogram is that *Aglaophyton* has more developed conducting tissue than the Horneophytopsida, but does not have true vascular tissue.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Unlike red and green algae, glaucophytes are not known to be ever involved in such secondary endosymbiosis events.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Archaeplastid cells typically lack centrioles and have mitochondria with flat cristae.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] They usually have a cell wall that contains cellulose, and photosynthesized carbohydrates are stored intracellularly in the form of starch, but these characteristics are also shared with other eukaryotes.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Different archaeplastid clades differ slightly in cellular biochemistry.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Red algae are pigmented with chlorophyll *a* and phycobiliproteins like most cyanobacteria, and accumulate starch in the cytosol *outside* the chloroplasts.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Glaucophytes have typical cyanobacterial pigments like those of red algae, but their plastids (called cyanelles) differ in having a primitive peptidoglycan outer layer, and they display a blue-grey hue due to phycobiliproteins such as phycocyanin and allophycocyanin.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The main evidence that archaeplastids form a monophyletic group comes from genetic studies, which indicate their plastids likely had a single origin.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] This evidence is however disputed, and based on the evidence to date, it is not possible to definitively confirm or refute alternative evolutionary scenarios to a single primary endosymbiosis event.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Photosynthetic organisms with plastids of indirect origin (such as brown algae, euglenids, diatoms and dinoflagellates) do not belong to Archaeplastida and are instead grouped into numerous other protist classifications, making the term "algae" a rather vague polyphyletic group.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Archaeplastida should not be confused with the older and obsolete name Archiplastideae, which refers to cyanobacteria and other groups of bacteria.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The consensus in 2005, when the group consisting of the glaucophytes and red and green algae and land plants was named 'Archaeplastida', was that it was a clade, i.e. was monophyletic.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Many studies published since then have provided evidence in agreement.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Other studies, though, have suggested that the group is paraphyletic.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] To date, the situation appears unresolved, but a strong signal for Plantae (Archaeplastida) monophyly has been demonstrated in a recent study (with an enrichment of red algal genes).
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The assumption made here is that Archaeplastida is a valid clade.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Various names have been given to the group.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Some authors have simply referred to the group as plants or Plantae.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] However, the name Plantae is ambiguous, since it has also been applied to less inclusive clades, such as Viridiplantae and embryophytes.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] To distinguish, the larger group is sometimes known as Plantae *sensu lato* ("plants in the broad sense").
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] To avoid ambiguity, other names have been proposed.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Primoplantae, which appeared in 2004, seems to be the first new name suggested for this group.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Another name applied to this node is Plastida, defined as the clade sharing "plastids of primary (direct prokaryote) origin [as] in *Magnolia virginiana* Linnaeus 1753".
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Although many studies have suggested the Archaeplastida form a monophyletic group, a 2009 paper argues that they are in fact paraphyletic.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The enrichment of novel red algal genes in a recent study, however, demonstrates a strong signal for Plantae (Archaeplastida) monophyly and an equally strong signal of gene sharing history between the red/green algae and other lineages.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] This study provides insight on how rich mesophilic red algal gene data are crucial for testing controversial issues in eukaryote evolution and for understanding the complex patterns of gene inheritance in protists.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Thus, the phylum name 'Glaucophyta' and the class name 'Rhodophyceae' appear at the same level in their classification.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The divisions proposed for the Archaeplastida are shown below in both tabular and diagrammatic form.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Red algae form one of the largest groups of algae.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Most are seaweeds, being multicellular and marine.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] for the group made up of the green algae and land plants (embryophytes).
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Except where lost secondarily, all have chloroplasts without a peptidoglycan layer and lack phycobiliproteins.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Adl et al. employ a narrow definition of the Chlorophyta; other sources include the Chlorodendrales and Prasinophytae, which may themselves be combined.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] ), as well as the land plants (embryophytes).
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Below is a consensus reconstruction of the relationships of Archaeplastida with its nearest neighbours, mainly based on molecular data.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] There has been disagreement near the Archaeplastida root, e.g. whether Cryptista emerged within the Archaeplastida.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] In 2014 a thorough review was published on these inconsistencies.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The position of Telonemia and Picozoa are not clear.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Also Hacrobia (Haptista + Cryptista) may be completely associated with the SAR clade.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The SAR are often seen as eukaryote-eukaryote hybrids, contributing to the confusion in the genetic analyses.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] A sister of *Gloeomargarita lithophora* has been engulfed by an ancestor of the Archaeplastida, leading to the plastids which are living in permanent endosymbiosis in most of the descendant lineages.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Because both *Gloeomargarita* and related cyanobacteria, in addition to the most primitive archaeplastids, all live in freshwater, it seems the Archaeplastida originated in freshwater, and only colonized the oceans in the late Proterozoic.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] In 2019, a phylogeny of the Archaeplastida based on genomes and transcriptomes from 1,153 plant species was proposed.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The placing of algal groups is supported by phylogenies based on genomes from the Mesostigmatophyceae and Chlorokybophyceae that have since been sequenced.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Both the "chlorophyte algae" and the "streptophyte algae" are treated as paraphyletic (vertical bars beside phylogenetic tree diagram) in this analysis.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The classification of Bryophyta is supported both by Puttick *et al.* 2018, and by phylogenies involving the hornwort genomes that have also since been sequenced.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Recent work on non-photosynthetic algae places Rhodelphidia as sister to Rhodophyta or to Glaucophyta and Viridiplantae; and Picozoa sister to that pair of groups.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] All archaeplastidans have plastids (chloroplasts) that carry out photosynthesis and are believed to be derived from endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] In glaucophytes, perhaps the most primitive members of the group, the chloroplast is called a *cyanelle* and shares several features with cyanobacteria, including a peptidoglycan cell wall, that are not retained in other members of the group.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The resemblance of cyanelles to cyanobacteria supports the endosymbiotic theory.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The cells of most archaeplastidans have walls, commonly but not always made of cellulose.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The Archaeplastida vary widely in the degree of their cell organization, from isolated cells to filaments to colonies to multi-celled organisms.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The earliest were unicellular, and many groups remain so today.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Multicellularity evolved separately in several groups, including red algae, ulvophyte green algae, and in the green algae that gave rise to stoneworts and land plants.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Because the ancestral archaeplastidan is hypothesized to have acquired its chloroplasts directly by engulfing cyanobacteria, the event is known as a *primary endosymbiosis* (as reflected in the name chosen for the group 'Archaeplastida' i.e.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] In 2013 it was discovered that one species of green algae, *Cymbomonas tetramitiformis* in the order Pyramimonadales, is a mixotroph and able to support itself through both phagotrophy and phototrophy.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] It is not yet known if this is a primitive trait and therefore defines the last common ancestor of Archaeplastida, which could explain how it obtained its chloroplasts, or if it is a trait regained by horizontal gene transfer.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Since then more species of mixotrophic green algae, such as *Pyramimonas tychotreta* and *Mantoniella antarctica*, has been found.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Evidence for primary endosymbiosis includes the presence of a double membrane around the chloroplasts; one membrane belonged to the bacterium, and the other to the eukaryote that captured it.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Over time, many genes from the chloroplast have been transferred to the nucleus of the host cell through endosymbiotic gene transfer (EGT).
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] It is estimated that 6–20% of the archaeplastidan genome consist of genes transferred from the endosymbiont.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The presence of such genes in the nuclei of eukaryotes without chloroplasts suggests this transfer happened early in the evolution of the group.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Other eukaryotes with chloroplasts appear to have gained them by engulfing a single-celled archaeplastidan with its own bacterially-derived chloroplasts.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Because these events involve endosymbiosis of cells that have their own endosymbionts, the process is called *secondary endosymbiosis*.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The chloroplasts of such eukaryotes are typically surrounded by more than two membranes, reflecting a history of multiple engulfment.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The chloroplasts of euglenids, chlorarachniophytes and a small group of dinoflagellates appear to be captured green algae, whereas those of the remaining photosynthetic eukaryotes, such as heterokont algae, cryptophytes, haptophytes, and dinoflagellates, appear to be captured red algae.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Perhaps the most ancient remains of Archaeplastida are putative red algae (*Rafatazmia*) within stromatolites in 1600 Ma (million years ago) rocks in India, as well as possible alga fossils (*Tuanshanzia*) from China's Gaoyuzhuang Biota of a similar age.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Somewhat more recent are microfossils from the Roper group in northern Australia.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The structure of these single-celled fossils resembles that of modern green algae.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] They date to the Mesoproterozoic Era, about 1500 to 1300 Ma.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] These fossils are consistent with a molecular clock study that calculated that this clade diverged about 1500 Ma.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] The oldest fossil that can be assigned to a specific modern group is the red alga *Bangiomorpha*, from 1200 Ma.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] In the late Neoproterozoic Era, algal fossils became more numerous and diverse.
[src:archaeplastida/archaeplastida] Eventually, in the Paleozoic Era, plants emerged onto land, and have continued to flourish up to the present.
